In the Azure ecosystem, "Managed Identity" is a specific type of Workload Identity.
While Managed Identity is the favorite for Azure-native services (like your AKS cluster), 
you will encounter other identity types depending on whether your app is running inside Azure, in a different cloud (like AWS), or in your local Jenkins pipeline.

Here is the breakdown of the other identities you should know:
1. Service Principal (The Traditional "App Account"):
    A Service Principal is essentially a "User Account for an Application."
    Unlike Managed Identities, which Azure manages for you, you are responsible for a Service Principal.
    Authentication: Uses a Client Secret (password) or a Certificate.
    When to use: Use this for things outside of Azure. 
                 For example, your Jenkins server likely uses a Service Principal to push images to your ACR.
    Risk: If you check the Client Secret into Git, anyone can access your Azure resources. 
          This is why Managed Identity is preferred for apps inside Azure.

2. Workload Identity (The AKS Specialist):
    This is a specific "bridge" identity for Kubernetes.
    Since a Pod in AKS isn't a "real" Azure resource (it's a container), it needs a way to prove who it is.
    How it works: It links a Kubernetes Service Account to a User-Assigned Managed Identity using a "Federated Credential." 
    Why it's the best for you: It allows each microservice Pod to have its own unique identity, rather than sharing the "Node's" identity. 
    Verification: You'll see an annotation in your Kubernetes YAML: azure.workload.identity/client-id.

3. User Identity (Human Identity):
    This represents you—the developer. When you run az login on your local Linux machine, you are using a User Identity.
    Local Development: Your Java code's DefaultAzureCredential will automatically use your logged-in user identity if it can't find a Managed Identity. 
    This allows you to test the same code on your laptop that runs in the cloud.

Identity Type          Managed by    Uses Secrets?    Best For
System-Assigned MI    Azure          No                One-to-one mapping (e.g., one VM).
User-Assigned MI      You/Azure      No                Sharing one ID across many microservices.
Service Principal      You          Yes                Jenkins, GitHub Actions, or apps on-prem.
Workload Identity      K8s + Azure  No                Individual Pods in your AKS cluster.

How to Check These in the Azure Portal:
    For Managed Identities: Search for "Managed Identities" in the top bar. You will see your standalone User-Assigned IDs here.
    For Service Principals: Search for "App Registrations". This is the "Blueprint" for the identity.
                            Then look under "Enterprise Applications" to see the actual "Instance" that has the permissions.
    For Permissions: On any resource (like your Service Bus), go to Access Control (IAM) and look for the names of these identities.

1. The Foundation: VNet & Subnet
    A VNet (Virtual Network) is your private "Gated Community" in Azure. It isolates your resources from the rest of the internet.
    VNet: The entire boundary of your network (e.g., 10.0.0.0/16).
    Subnet: A smaller "Neighborhood" inside the VNet (e.g., 10.0.1.0/24).
    In AKS: 
        Your Nodes (the VMs) live in a specific subnet. 
        Depending on your configuration (Azure CNI), your Pods might also take IP addresses from this same subnet.
2. The Workforce: Node Pools
    A Node Pool is a group of identical virtual machines that run your Kubernetes workloads. 
    System Node Pool: The "Utility Workers." 
        This pool hosts critical system services (like DNS and metrics) that keep the cluster alive. 
        You usually don't put your own apps here.
    User Node Pool: The "Business District."
        This is where your Java microservices run. 
        You can have different pools for different needs (e.g., a GPU Pool for AI or a High-Memory Pool for heavy databases).

Term                          What it is                                    Why it matters
CIDR                          The IP address range format (e.g., /24).      Determines how many "addresses" (Nodes/Pods) you can fit in your subnet.
NSG(Network Security Group)   A "Security Guard" at the subnet gate.        It contains rules (Allow/Deny) that control which traffic can reach your nodes.
Private Endpoint              A "Secret Entrance."                          Lets your AKS cluster talk to services like SQL or Key Vault over a private IP, never touching the public internet.
Azure CNI vs Overlay          The "Plumbing" model.                         CNI: Every Pod gets a real VNet IP. Overlay: Pods get private internal IPs, saving VNet space.

Where is this used in your workflow?
  When you run your Ansible playbooks, you are often defining these very things:
  VNet/Subnet: Your Ansible code checks if the subnet exists before deploying the cluster.
  Node Pool Sizing: You specify in your YAML how many nodes (e.g., node_count: 3) should be in your userpool.
  NSG Rules: Ansible can automate opening Port 443 so your microservice is reachable.

1. The Infrastructure Layer (VNet & Subnet)
      This is the "ground" your cluster sits on.
      Where to find it: Search for Virtual Networks in the top search bar.
      How to check: 
          1. Select your VNet (e.g., my-vnet).
          2. Click Subnets on the left menu.
          3. Look for the subnet assigned to AKS. You can see the Available IP addresses here—if this number is low, your cluster won't be able to scale.
          4. Click Connected devices to see the actual Network Interfaces (NICs) of your cluster nodes.
2. The Compute Layer (Cluster, Node Pools & Nodes)
      This is the "hardware" managing your containers.
      Where to find it: Search for Kubernetes services.
      How to check Node Pools: 
          1. Select your AKS cluster.
          2. Under Settings, click Node pools.
          3. Here you see the "System" and "User" pools, their status, and the VM size (e.g., Standard_DS2_v2).
      How to check individual Nodes:
          Inside the cluster menu, look under Kubernetes resources and click Nodes.
          This shows you the health, CPU usage, and Memory pressure of each physical VM in the pool.
3. The Workload Layer (Deployments, Pods & Services)
      These are the "Logical" items inside Kubernetes. Historically, you had to use the command line (kubectl) for this, but the Azure Portal now has a built-in view.
      Where to find it: Inside your AKS Cluster page, look for the Kubernetes resources section on the left sidebar.

In a microservices architecture, the Load Balancer and API Gateway (Apigee) work together to handle two different types of traffic:
External (North-South) traffic coming from users, and Internal (East-West) traffic between your services.

Load Balancer (Layer 4): 
    Acts as the "Traffic Cop" at the network level.
    It distributes raw TCP/UDP traffic across your AKS nodes.
    In Azure, when you create a Kubernetes service of type: LoadBalancer, Azure automatically spins up a Standard Load Balancer in your resource group.
Apigee (Layer 7):
    Acts as the "Concierge."
    It sits in front of your microservices to handle API keys, rate limiting, security policies, and transformation. 
    It doesn't just route traffic; it manages the API.

How to Connect the Load Balancer in Java/AKS
To connect your Java microservice to a load balancer, you define a Kubernetes Service.
For Public Access:
        apiVersion: v1
        kind: Service
        metadata:
          name: java-microservice-public
        spec:
          type: LoadBalancer # This triggers the Azure Public Load Balancer
          ports:
            - port: 80
              targetPort: 8080 # Your Java app port
          selector:
            app: java-app
For Internal Access (Private IP):
    If you want a private load balancer that only Apigee or other internal services can see, use an annotation: 
    metadata:
      name: java-microservice-internal
      annotations:
        service.beta.kubernetes.io/azure-load-balancer-internal: "true"

Calling Between Services using Apigee and Load Balancer:
When Service A needs to call Service B, you have two main patterns:
Pattern A: Direct Service-to-Service (Performance)
      Service A calls Service B directly using the Kubernetes ClusterIP name (e.g., http://service-b).
      This bypasses the Load Balancer and Apigee entirely, which is faster and cheaper for internal communication.
Pattern B: Via Apigee (Governance & Security)
      If you need to enforce security policies (like OAuth or logging) even for internal calls,
      Service A calls the Apigee Proxy URL, which then routes the request back to Service B's Internal Load Balancer.

How to set this up in Apigee:
    Target Server: In Apigee, create a "Target Server" pointing to the Internal Load Balancer IP of Service B.
    API Proxy: Create a proxy in Apigee that uses this Target Server.
    The Call: Service A makes an HTTP request to https://api.yourcompany.com/service-b.

How to Verify the Connection
    Check the Load Balancer IP: Run kubectl get svc. Look at the EXTERNAL-IP column. For an internal LB, this will be a private IP (e.g., 10.0.x.x).
    Check Apigee Targets: In the Apigee UI, go to Develop > Target Endpoints. Ensure the URL matches your Load Balancer's IP or DNS name.
    Test the Path: From inside a pod in Service A, try to "curl" the Apigee endpoint:
    curl -v https://api.yourcompany.com/service-b/health
    If you get a 200 OK, the chain (Service A -> Apigee -> Load Balancer -> Service B) is successful.

Feature            Direct (ClusterIP)              Via Apigee + Load Balancer
LatencyExtremely   Low                             Moderate (due to Gateway hop)
Security           Minimal (Basic Network Policy)  High (OAuth, Threat Protection)
Observability      Kubernetes Logs                 Full API Analytics & Trace

Because you are using AKS, the "real" networking hardware lives in that special hidden Resource Group (the one starting with MC_).
Step A: Find the Load Balancer Resource
      In the Azure Portal, search for Resource groups.
      Look for the one named MC_[YourResourceGroup]_[YourClusterName]_[Location]. 
      Inside this group, look for a resource of type Load balancer (usually named kubernetes).
Step B: Verify the IP Address (Frontend IP)
      Click on that Load Balancer resource.
      On the left menu, click Frontend IP configuration.  
      What to look for:
            You will see the IP address here. 
            If it's a Private IP (e.g., 10.x.x.x), it is an Internal Load Balancer. 
            If it's a Public IP, it's reachable from the internet.
Step C: Verify the "Health" of your Java App (Backend Pools)
      Click on Backend pools in the same menu.
      Click on the pool (usually named kubernetes).
      What to look for:
            You should see a list of your AKS Nodes. 
            If the "Health State" is not 100%, it means your Java app is crashing or the "Health Probe" is failing, and the Load Balancer is refusing to send traffic there.
Step D: Verify the Port Mapping (Load Balancing Rules)
      Click on Load balancing rules.
      What to look for:
            You will see a rule mapping the "Frontend Port" (usually 80 or 443) to the "Backend Port." 
            This confirms that traffic hitting the IP is actually being told where to go.

1. Azure Resource Group (The "Cloud" Container)
    A Resource Group (RG) is a logical container for Azure resources. In your workflow, this is handled via Azure CLI or Ansible.
    What it handles: Physical or virtual Azure assets like the AKS Cluster itself, Virtual Networks (VNet), Managed Identities, Key Vaults, and Storage Accounts.
    Usage: 
          Billing: You can see exactly how much your "Dev" environment costs versus "Production" by looking at the RG. 
          Lifecycle: If you delete the Resource Group, everything inside it (the cluster, the disks, the IPs) is deleted instantly. 
          Access (RBAC): You can give a developer permission to manage one Resource Group without letting them touch the rest of the subscription.
2. Kubernetes Namespace (The "Cluster" Partition)
    A Namespace is a virtual cluster inside your physical AKS cluster. This is handled via kubectl or your Ansible k8s module.
    What it handles: Kubernetes-specific objects like Pods, Services, Deployments, ConfigMaps, and Secrets.
    Usage: 
        Isolation: You can run the same microservice in a dev namespace and a test namespace on the same cluster without them crashing into each other.
        Resource Quotas: You can limit a namespace so it only uses, for example, 4GB of RAM, preventing one buggy microservice from crashing the whole cluster.
        Security: Using "Network Policies," you can block traffic between namespaces (e.g., the frontend namespace cannot talk directly to the db namespace).

How to check them in your environment
To check Resource Groups:
    Go to the Azure Portal and search for "Resource groups." 
    You will likely see your main group and that "hidden" MC_ group I mentioned earlier which handles the networking.
To check Namespaces:
    Via Portal: Go to your AKS Cluster > Kubernetes resources > Namespaces.
    Via Terminal: Run kubectl get ns.
    You will see defaults like default, kube-system, and likely your own (e.g., tif-dev).
